[7] Philippines (NCR)
Date: Wed 11 Dec 2013
Source: GMA News [edited]
http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/339346/news/metromanila/doh-issues-measles-alert-in-ncr-as-cases-rise


The Department of Health [DOH] on Wednesday [11 Dec 2013] advised residents in Metro Manila to take precautions against measles after noting 2 deaths and a rise in cases in at least 5 cities in the National Capital Region [NCR].

In a statement posted on the government website, DOH Metro Manila head Eduardo Janairo cited records showing a rapid rise in measles cases in Las Pinas, Muntinlupa, Caloocan, Manila, and Paranaque. "Everyone should take necessary precaution because measles is a severe disease that causes complications like ear infections, pneumonia and even inflammation of the brain. It is also highly contagious and can be spread easily through cough and sneeze and direct contact with affected persons through nose or mouth secretions," Janairo said. The DOH Metro Manila said its records showed the fatalities came from Malabon and Muntinlupa. It added that most of those affected were 1-4 years old, and most were male.

Janairo advised parents and guardians of children to look out for symptoms: "If you believe you have been exposed to someone with measles, you should watch for measles symptoms to appear after 9 days. Some persons can be affected immediately before the rash appears, 4 days after being exposed," he said. Janairo also advised the public to make sure they and members of their families are up to date on measles-mumps-rubella (MMR) vaccines and other age-appropriate immunisations. "Measles vaccination not only protects the person but also serves as safeguard to family members who are too young to get the vaccine or haven't received it yet. Receiving 2 doses of measles vaccine is highly effective in preventing measles," he said.

Citing partial reports from the Regional Epidemiology Surveillance Unit, the DOH said there were 179 confirmed measles cases from 1 Jan to 10 Dec 2013. It said this was 616 percent higher compared to the same period last year [2012], with only 25 cases recorded. For this year, the ages of cases ranged from one month to 37 years. Most of those affected were 1-4 years old, and most were male.

The cities with the largest numbers of measles cases were:
- Las Pinas, 44 cases
- Muntinlupa, 32
- Caloocan, 26
- Manila, 22
- Paranaque, 15
- Malabon, 10
- Quezon City, 8
- Taguig, 8
- Navotas, 7
- Pasay, 4
- Makati, 2
- Pasig, 1
- Mandaluyong, Marikina, San Juan and Valenzuela Cities, along with Pateros town, recorded zero cases so far.

Meanwhile, the DOH Metro Manila dispatched teams of nurses who will act as an Anti-Measles Task Force to identify areas in the NCR. It said the nurses will "assist in evaluating patients and provide the necessary vaccination to prevent further transmission of the disease." Janairo urged all parents and caregivers of children aged 0-12 years old to go the nearest health center and have their children immunized against measles.

Further, the DOH Metro Manila advised the public to report suspected measles cases to a health care provider before going to a hospital. It said a suspected measles case must 1st be evaluated as a precaution and protection for other patients and health workers from possible infection. The DOH noted measles can easily be spread through the air when an infected person talks, coughs, or sneezes. Measles infection in a pregnant woman can lead to miscarriage, premature birth, or a low birth-weight baby, it said. "Those who have developed symptoms of measles should stay away from public places such as work, school, child care settings, shops, and public transport to avoid putting others at risk," it said.

